<IFRAME FRAMEBORDER=1 ALIGN=CENTER width=100% HEIGHT=200 SCROLLING=YES SRC="http://boards.stratics.com/forums/Forum119/HTML/000125.html">
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width="95%"><TR><td bgcolor="#000000"><TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="100%"><TR bgcolor="#5C0000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#FFFFFF" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Maire'</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">I JUST got the message you may NOT trap this item if it is locked down.<BR>Since the whole theory behind the 'you own the house/trapping chests locked down in your house' concept was to protect items in YOUR house, that YOU owned...what gives?<BR>   You, i and my grandma know that most people simply locked the container down, trapped it, then released it...it was a spurious argument before...but we all used it anyhow...<BR>   So what do i do now?  Go red and leave my smith/tinker/tailor/carp in my house all the time and be glad she's not the miner or lumberer? or what?<BR>   My husband is out making PKs miserable all day and uses about 20 trapped boxes a day...i kill a LOT of would be PKs...  I don't PvP much, unless you count the *boom* that accompanies opening my boxes  <IMG SRC="http://boards.stratics.com/forums/wink.gif"><BR>   Is there a way around this?<BR>            Maire'(for Madette, GM mule gal)</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Maire'</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Additional info:<BR>   Madette (the tinker) OWNS the house.  <BR>   She locked the chests down with the MASTER key to the house in the TOP level of her pack.<BR>   I am a GM tinker.<BR>   I tried to make all three types of traps on the boxes (though boomers are my trap of choice) with the same message: "You may not set a trap on an item that is locked down"<BR>   I play Europa, though i suspect it won't make a difference.<BR>   I had the keys to the boxes in my pack, on a keyring<BR>              *grumbles*<BR>                   Maire'</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Cooperhawk</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">what happens when you trap it while it is on the floor but not locked down?  Have your husband open it & see if he is offered the ability to give you a count.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Elof of Europa</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">While actually trapping the box it should not be locked down. You can lock it down after but what would be the point, as anything in the box would be locked down (no thief would be able to steal so why open it?) or the items are not locked down (house lockdown limit or released) so they would decay, so you lose lose valuables anyway.<BR>I set traps like this:<BR>Create box<BR>Place box on floor (in a public building that I own as the tinker)<BR>Open box and put box key into my backpack<BR>Set trap<BR>Lock box<BR>Unlock box<BR>Put key back in box<P>I have made over 100 trapped boxes, using this method, with more than 30 kills (according to my customers. I never use them myself, as I am forgetful and open them   <IMG SRC="http://boards.stratics.com/forums/frown.gif"> ). Several of these where thieves snooping customers as they left   <IMG SRC="http://boards.stratics.com/forums/smile.gif"> to see what goodies they had bought. I have NEVER been reported for murder.<BR>Try it. Cooperhawks idea is good to, getting a friend to experiment is a good check.<P>------------------<BR>Elof - Senior Merchant GM for the Association. GM Smith/Tinker/Carpenter<BR>(The Whole Is Greater Than The Sum Of It's Parts)<BR><p>[This message has been edited by Elof of Europa (edited February 15, 2000).]</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE></td></tr></table> 
</IFRAME>
